 <strong>mse</strong> Mean squared error performance function.
 
  <a href="matlab:doc mse">mse</a>(net,targets,outputs,errorWeights,...parameters...) calculates a
  network performance given targets, outputs, error weights and parameters
  as the mean of squared errors.
 
  Only the first three arguments are required.  The default error weight
  is {1}, which weights the importance of all targets equally.

  'regularization' - a fraction between 0 (the default) and 1 indicating
     the proportion of performance attributed to weight/bias values. The
     larger this value the network will be penalized for large weights,
     and the more likely the network function will avoid overfitting.

    results in outputs and targets being normalized to [-1, +1], and
    therefore errors in the range [-2, +2), or 'percent' which normalizes

  <strong>simplify</strong> Fix degeneracies and intersections in a polyshape
 
  PG = <strong>simplify</strong>(pshape) simplifies the input polyshape by resolving all
  boundary intersections and improper nesting, removing duplicate vertices
  and degeneracies.
 
  PG = <strong>simplify</strong>(..., 'KeepCollinearPoints', tf) specifies how to treat 
  consecutive vertices lying along a straight line. tf can be one of the 
  following:
    true  - Keep all collinear points as vertices of PG.
    false - Remove collinear points so that PG contains the fewest number
            of necessary vertices.
  If this name-value pair is not specified, then <strong>simplify</strong> uses the value of
  'KeepCollinearPoints' that was used when creating the input polyshape.
 
  See also <a href="matlab:help polyshape">polyshape</a>, <a href="matlab:help polyshape/issimplified">issimplified</a>, <a href="matlab:help polyshape/intersect">intersect</a>, <a href="matlab:help polyshape/addboundary">addboundary</a>
